# React Component Patterns

  

## Page Components Are Thin Orchestrators

  

Pages live in `src/pages/`. Their only jobs are: fetch data via hooks, derive minimal local state, and pass everything down to presentational children. They must not contain significant JSX logic, styling blocks, or UI sub-components inline.

  

```tsx

// ❌ BAD — page doing too much

export function StudentsPage() {

  const { data } = useStudents();

  return (

    <div>

      <div className="flex items-center ...">

        <input onChange={...} />

        <select>...</select>

      </div>

      <table>

        {data?.map(s => <tr><td>...</td></tr>)}

      </table>

    </div>

  );

}

  

// ✅ GOOD — page delegates to focused children

export function StudentsPage() {

  const { data, isLoading, isError } = useStudents();

  const [filter, setFilter] = useState("");

  return <StudentTable students={data} isLoading={isLoading} filter={filter} onFilterChange={setFilter} />;

}

```

  

## Sub-Components Do One Thing

  

UI components live in `src/components/` or co-located alongside the page file. Each component should have a single, named responsibility — not be a catch-all. Prefer many small focused components over one large one.

  

```tsx

// ❌ BAD — catch-all component

function StudentCard({ student, comms, onEdit, onDelete, showBadge }) { ... }

  

// ✅ GOOD — focused components composed together

function StudentRow({ student }: { student: Student }) { ... }

function StudentBadge({ grade }: { grade: string }) { ... }

function StudentActions({ onEdit, onDelete }: StudentActionsProps) { ... }

```

  

## Co-location Rule

  

If a sub-component is only used by one page, it may live in a file alongside that page (e.g. `Students.tsx` + `StudentRow.tsx` in `src/pages/`). If it's used in two or more places, move it to `src/components/`.

  

## Conventions

  

### Data Fetching — Custom Hooks Per Resource

  

Each unique API resource gets its own custom hook that wraps TanStack Query. One hook per resource type, named after the resource.

  

```ts

// ✅ GOOD — one hook per resource

useStudents(); // GET /api/v1/students (list)

useStudent(id); // GET /api/v1/students/:id (single)

useCommunications(filter); // GET /api/v1/communications

useDocuments(); // GET /api/v1/documents

```

  

Hooks live in `src/hooks/`. Page components call hooks; they never call `apiClient` directly.

  

### Helper Functions — Co-location vs. Shared Utils

  

We prefer WET over DRY here: one duplication is intentional and acceptable. The rule triggers at **three instances** — when a helper appears in a third file, extract it to `src/utils/` and import it everywhere.

  

```ts

// ✅ GOOD — used in one file, lives there

// inside Students.tsx

function gradeColor(grade: string): string { ... }

  

// ✅ GOOD — duplicated in two files, leave it

// Students.tsx has initials(), Dashboard.tsx has initials() — fine

  

// ❌ BAD — same helper in three or more files → extract

// src/utils/display.ts

export function initials(name: string): string { ... }

export function formatDate(iso: string | null): string { ... }

```

  

The `src/utils/` directory already contains `roles.ts`. Add new util files per concern (e.g. `display.ts` for formatting, `dates.ts` for date helpers).